Row and column constraints give sum_j A_{i,j}=25 for every i and sum_i B_{i,j}=25 for every j. To avoid attacks across block boundaries, horizontal adjacency forces A to be constant along each column (the king in a block is always in the same row within its column), and vertical adjacency forces B to be constant along each row (the king in a block is always in the same column within its row). Hence A is determined by choosing which 25 of the 50 block-columns are entirely top, giving C(50,25) possibilities; B is determined by choosing which 25 of the 50 block-rows are entirely left, giving another C(50,25) possibilities. Each pair (A,B) yields a unique arrangement, so the total number is
\boxed{\binom{50}{25}^{2}}

PLAN
- Since 64 = 2^6, every factor in a multiplicative partition is a power of 2: 2^{a_i} with a_i ≥ 1.
- The product requires sum a_i = 6, so multiplicative partitions of 64 correspond to unordered partitions of the integer 6.
- Therefore P(64) = p(6), where p is the partition function.
- Recall p(6) = 11, via the 11 partitions of 6.

SOLUTION
- Each partition of 6 into positive integers a_1, ..., a_k (sum 6) yields a multiplicative partition of 64 as 2^{a_1} · ... · 2^{a_k}.
- The 11 partitions of 6 and their corresponding multiplicative partitions of 64 are:
  64;
  2 × 32;
  4 × 16;
  2 × 2 × 16;
  8 × 8;
  2 × 4 × 8;
  2 × 2 × 2 × 8;
  4 × 4 × 4;
  4 × 4 × 2 × 2;
  4 × 2 × 2 × 2 × 2;
  2 × 2 × 2 × 2 × 2 × 2.

CHECK
- The count matches p(6) = 11, and each corresponds to a unique unordered multiplicative partition of 64; no other partitions exist since every factor must be a power of 2.

FINAL
\boxed{11}

